a Convention on Mercury goes into effect Aug. 16, 2017. With the activation of this international treaty to protect human health and the environment from human emissions of mercury and its compounds, 92 countries including the EU will begin obeying comprehensive regulations on mercury from mining to disposal.  JICA is providing various assistance in this area. JICA's Kyus...hu International Center has been holding annual training sessions since 2014, teaching about the background of Minamata disease and the convention, and giving examples of Japan's anti-mercury pollution technology. Twenty-two government officials from 11 countries have participated in the training over three years, and it is planned again for this year. In Latin American countries such as Nicaragua and Uruguay, JICA and its partner governments are carrying out capacity building for surveying and analyzing mercury and on river mercury monitoring. In recent years, JICA has also begun a project with Japanese companies and local governments to spread and promote to other countries methods of properly processing mercury. See MoreJapan International Cooperation Agency - JICA · July 10 at 1:01am · JICA Vice President Takao Toda’s interview on Universal Health Coverage has been published in Devex, July 5. “From a global perspective, we have very, very big room for potential for Japan to be more proactive in global health”, Toda commented. Please have a look!The stumbling blocks to JICA's UHC pushThe Japan International Cooperation Agency's vice president for human security and global health, Takao Toda, spoke to Devex on the bilateral aid agency's current efforts to promote universal health coverage.devex.comSee More





